entry.title: Petroica boodang
entry.content: Giving a bit of colour to winter in the Macedon Ranges. I'm not sure what the small olive birds are that these robins tend to hang around with. They are too fast for me to get a photo of.

entry.title: Coracina novaehollandiae
entry.content: A family group of black-faced cuckoo-shrikes flying from tree to tree. Juveniles calling loudly and begging for food.

entry.title: Sericornis frontalis
entry.content: Juvenile or female. The bird was so tame/inquisitive I could use my close-up lens! Note the pale grey eye colour of this individual. The eyes are more often pale yellow, I think.

entry.title: Callocephalon fimbriatum
entry.content: One of a noisy flock of 10 Gang-gang Cockatoos feeding on grubs in an Acacia mearnsii. They all looked to be young males with developing red head-feathering. They were quite unfazed by my close presence.

entry.title: Threskiornis molucca
entry.content: Occasionally a fearless lone white ibis wanders around our backyard.

entry.title: Dacelo novaeguineae
entry.content: Sitting on the window-sill watching its reflection. It let me get VERY close and stayed there for around 5 minutes then flew off. Very beautiful.

entry.title: Lichenostomus chrysops
entry.content: Feeding on cultivated Eucalyptus crenulata. Blue eyes.

entry.title: Melithreptus lunatus
entry.content: Comparison of adult and immature White-naped Honeyeater. The immature bird has a brown head and the eye crescent and base of bill are both orange.

entry.title: Oriolus sagittatus
entry.content: We have been seeing this bird feeding on the small grapes on the vine on our verandah. It takes fright easily but the shape, size and black-streaks on the white belly give a positive identification. It flies off quickly with the slightest disturbance before a photo can be taken.

entry.title: Daphoenositta chrysoptera pileata
entry.content: Male. 2nd pic shows typical upside-down foraging position while searching for insects. Group of about a dozen birds. This seems to be one of the most eastern records for Race pileata. See female in 9022.

entry.title: Daphoenositta chrysoptera pileata
entry.content: Female. Group of about a dozen birds. This seems to be one of the most eastern records for Race pileata. See also 9023.

entry.title: Podargus strigoides
entry.content: Pair spotted roosting on a dead Blackwood, among Eucalyptus aromaphloia. Second pic shows wing-marks on our window - the birds are feasting on Rain Moths (Hepialidae) on the windows at night at this time of year.
